The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, May 26, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Prakash Gupta, a realtor based in Howrah, was arrested at his residence on Banbihari Bose Road in connection with the death of a 12-year-old girl, Jyoti Gupta. The arrest was made on the basis of an FIR lodged at the Howrah police station by the Howrah Municipal Corporation. The girl was killed on Thursday, when a portion of a wall of a building under construction fell on her from the third floor. Gupta was the promoter of the building on Rajballav Saha Lane. According to police, he was produced in court and remanded in jail custody for a week.																																																		Mayor Subrata Mukherjee wrote to union minister of water resources Priya Ranjan Das Munshi, asking for funds to check the erosion of the Hooghly adjacent to the Calcutta Municipal Corporations waterworks at Palta. The mayor said Palta Waterworks was the CMCs mainstay ensuring supply of filtered surface water to 10 million people. Municipal affairs minister Asok Bhattacharaya agreed to lend support to mayor Subrata Mukherjees demand for central funds for Calcuttas development. 																																																		Mayor Subrata Mukherjee has summoned a meeting on Monday with councillors of wards 115 and 122, which are opposing the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authoritys Behala and Bansdroni booster pumping station project. The people of these wards are demanding a direct supply of drinking water and do not want the dedicated water pipeline from Garden Reach to bypass their area. Well have to make some arrangements for them, Mukherjee said. On Tuesday he met municipal affairs minister Asok Bhattacharaya at Writers Buildings to draw his attention to the disturbances created by CPM local leaders in the two wards, causing delay in laying pipelines of Garfa and Bansdroni booster pumping stations. 																																																		A 21-year-old youth, Ram Bahadur, was seriously injured on Tuesday morning on Chowringhee Road in the Shakespeare Sarani police station area when a private bus on route 47B hit him. Police said Bahadur was crossing the road when the accident took place at around 11 am. He was taken to SSKM Hospital in a critical condition and is undergoing treatment. The driver of the bus was arrested and the vehicle was impounded.																																																		Four employees of the Calcutta Municipal Corporations conservancy department were showcaused on Tuesday for neglecting their duties. Member of the mayor-in-council Rajib Deb, Swapan Mahapatra and Arun Sarkar had visited ward 17 and 27 without prior notice, and found the four employees chatting with others outside their wards during their duty hours. All four have been ordered to reply within seven days or face suspension.To American Center for donating books worth $3,000 to the Central Detective Training School in the city
